 juli 1429","1319":"1319","1429":"1429","Loire, Rhône-Alpes, France":"Loire, Rhône-Alpes, Frankrijk","Rohan, Morbihan, Brittany":"Guilliers, Morbihan, Bretagne, Frankrijk","Abbaye Notre Dame de Bon Repos, Bretagne, France":"Bretagne, Frankrijk","Guilliers, Morbihan, Bretagne, France":"Guilliers, Morbihan, Bretagne, Frankrijk","Chateau de La Chèze, France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"1351–25 July 1429":"1351–25 July 1429","1351–1429":"1351–1429","1378–Male":"1378–Deceased","1356–1448":"1356–1448","1319–Female":"1319–Deceased","1382–1462":"1382–1462","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1324–1403":"1324–1403","1462":"1462","1351":"1351","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","20 November 1403":"20 November 1403","1448":"1448","1403":"1403","1324":"1324","1356":"1356","1378":"1378","25 July 1429":"25 July 1429","1319":"1319","1429":"1429","Loire, Rhône-Alpes, France":"Loire, Rhône-Alpes, France","Rohan, Morbihan, Brittany":"Guilliers, Morbihan, Brittany, France","Abbaye Notre Dame de Bon Repos, Bretagne, France":"Brittany, France","Guilliers, Morbihan, Bretagne, France":"Guilliers, Morbihan, Brittany, France","Chateau de La Chèze, France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rohan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brigid, Kieran, Oonagh, Padraig, Siobhan.","Irish (Kerry and Cork): from <b>Ó Ruadhacháin</b> or <b>Ó Robhacháin</b>, see   Rowan  .","Breton and English: habitational name from Rohan in Morbihan, Brittany (France)."],"variants":[{"name":"Rowan","meanings":["Irish: from <b>Ó Ruadháin</b> or <b>Ó Ruaidhín</b>, both meaning ‘descendant of <i>Ruadhán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>ruadh</i> ‘red’. See also   Rooney  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Ruadhacháin</b>, ‘son of <i>Ruadhachán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>ruadh</i> ‘red’ (also used as a placename and Anglicized as <i>Roughan</i>). Compare also   Rogan   (<b>Ó Ruadhagáin</b>), of which may be a variant, both it and <b>Ó Ruadhacháin</b> being found in Ulster and Connacht.","Irish: from <b>Ó Robhacháin</b>, the name of a scattered ecclesiastical family, found in Clare in the 16th and 17th centuries. The personal name was earlier <i>Reabhachán</i> ‘skillful, artful’."]}]},{"name":"Alain","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Breton form of <i>Alan</i>, now common in all parts of France.  See  <b>Alan</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"VIII,","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine pet form of   Vivien   and   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]},{"name":"sire","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pronounced ‘<b>shee</b>-la’; derived in the early Middle Ages from Anglo-Norman <i>Cecile</i>.  See  <b>Cecily</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Shilla","meanings":["Modern coinage, apparently an altered form of   Sheila ."]},{"name":"Sheelah","meanings":["Pronounced ‘<b>shee</b>-la’; derived in the early Middle Ages from Anglo-Norman <i>Cecile</i>.  See  <b>Cecily</b>   ."]},{"name":"Sheila","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of <i>Síle</i>, the Irish Gaelic form of   Cecily .  This name has become so common and widespread that it is hardly felt to be Irish any longer. In Australia since the 19th century it has been a slang generic term for any woman."]},{"name":"Shelagh","meanings":["Variant of   Sheila .  The final consonants in the written form seem to have been added to give a Gaelic feel to the name. There is no etymological justification for them."]},{"name":"Shayla","meanings":["Recent coinage, apparently a variant of   Sheila ."]},{"name":"Sheelagh","meanings":["Pronounced ‘<b>shee</b>-la’; derived in the early Middle Ages from Anglo-Norman <i>Cecile</i>.  See  <b>Cecily</b>   ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]},{"name":"Léon,","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Derivative of   Leo  , from the oblique case. This form is common as a Jewish name, but recently has also acquired wider currency. The lion is an important symbol among Jews because of Jacob's dying pronouncement that ‘Judah is a lion's whelp’ (Genesis 49:9)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alain VIII, sire de Léon, Vicomte de 1396 à 1429 de Rohan was born in 1351, in Guilliers, Morbihan, Brittany, France as the son of Jean I Vicomte de Rohan. He married Beatrix de Clisson Comtesse de Porhoet in 1380, in Loire, Rhône-Alpes, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 3 daughters. He died on 25 July 1429, in France, at the age of 78, and was buried in Brittany, France."},"et":{"1351–25 July 1429":"1351–25. juuli 1429","1351–1429":"1351–1429","1378–Male":"1378–Surnud","1356–1448":"1356–14